{
  "text": "which has been labeled as the \"generalized Jacobian\" matrix [CITATION_1] . Note that the columns of N c form a basis for the null-space of H c . Matrices of the type JN occur naturally after the elimination of equality constraints. The machinery of such elimination, however, permits choosing matrices N of various properties and sizes, e.g., N could be chosen to be a projection matrix, in which case JN is sometimes referred to as a \"restricted Jacobian\" [CITATION_2] . Depending on the specific application, various names can be encountered. For example several elimination steps on the hierarchy (\u03c9 = 0) \u227b (5) \u227b (6) lead to the so called \"fixed-attitude restricted Jacobian\" [CITATION_3] . In [CITATION_4] , JN has been called a \"task-consistent posture Jacobian\" etc.",
